  <h2>Bench QC vs listing theatre</h2>
  <p>
    Seller galleries optimise conversion; warehouse benches optimise accountability. The gap between the two is normal, not scandalous. Your job is deciding whether the delta matters enough to pause shipping—not whether Discord hype matched studio renders.
  </p>

  <h2>Five checkpoints before approving exports</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Palette drift:</strong> compare dye lots under harsh bench lighting vs listing softboxes.</li>
    <li><strong>Hardware geometry:</strong> zippers, snaps, eyelets—misalignment visible at 100% zoom matters.</li>
    <li><strong>Textile tension:</strong> knits and mesh distort differently once stuffed in poly bags.</li>
    <li><strong>Measurement cues:</strong> if listings promised tailoring aids, confirm tags or rulers appear.</li>
    <li><strong>Dimensional honesty:</strong> chunky soles or puffy fills preview volumetric surprise downstream.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Where this sits in the Spreadsheet cadence</h2>
  <p>
    Discovery happens in indexed lanes; budgets settle inside Mulebuy. QC is the bridge—capture discrepancies while freight is still domestic-adjacent. After you accept an international label, remedies narrow quickly regardless of what a worksheet cell claimed last Tuesday.
  </p>

